;; slat-render-strategy-2026-07-13.slat
;; Lacuna Engineering — SLAT render strategy: extending render-ref.mjs
;; from a per-verb reference renderer to a general SLAT→(HTML|terminal|IDE|
;; search|LLM-ingest) pipeline that also treats code as first-class records.
;;
;; Authored: 2026-07-13
;; Audience: Alfred + future engineering agents
;; Format:   SLAT, dogfooding the very thing we're specifying
;; Status:   proposal — Phase-0 estimates real, later phases TBD

(strategy-doc
  :id             "slat-render-strategy-2026-07-13"
  :owner          "Lacuna Engineering"
  :date           #inst "2026-07-13T00:00:00Z"
  :for            "Alfred"
  :subject        "SLAT rendering — extend render-ref.mjs into a general pipeline"
  :related-docs   ("~/code/curator/scheme-books/book-of-slat/00-cover.slat"
                   "~/code/curator/scheme-books/book-of-slat/01-what-a-slat-is.slat"
                   "~/code/curator/scheme-books/book-of-slat/04-the-slat-record.slat"
                   "~/code/scheme-lang/docs/site/render-ref.mjs"
                   "~/code/curator/BOOK/BOOK-INVENTORY.jsonl")
  :sections       9)

;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 1 — State of the union
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     1
  :title "State of the union — what SLAT already specifies and what render-ref.mjs already does"
  :prose
"Book of SLAT already nails the substrate.

Chapter 1 fixes the round-trip property: whatever you write, you can read
back — byte-identical, across every binding. Chapter 4 fixes the record
shape: head symbol at position 0, then keys and positional values, plus a
reserved `:_` namespace for reader-internal fields (`:_form`,
`:_positional`, `:_comment`, `:_meta`). The cover promises sixteen chapters
plus ten appendices covering canonicalization, content-addressing, signing,
auto-assembly, and the fifteen record types. That work is done. SLAT is a
usable, honest wire format today.

What SLAT does NOT specify — and what tonight raises — is what to DO with a
SLAT record once you have it: how a `(chapter ... :prose \"...\")` record
turns into HTML the operator reads, how it turns into a terminal page a kid
running `sakura-scheme repl` sees, how it turns into an IDE hover card, how
it turns into a search result, how it turns into a training chunk. The spec
today stops at 'here is the shape'. The renderer does not exist yet — for
books.

`render-ref.mjs` is the closest thing we have. It reads the consolidated
reference SLAT (~1,157 verbs + 70 core forms) via `reference-loader.js`,
walks `ref.verbList` and `ref.coreList`, and emits `dist/reference.html`
with sidebar TOC, per-verb Signature/Summary/Explanation/Examples blocks,
Caveats/Drawbacks/Use-cases/Related lists, and Learn metadata. It carries a
Scheme highlighter (mirroring `src/repl/highlight.js`) that emits Run
buttons on `sakura-scheme` fences. And it handles a limited MD subset
inside `doc-body` strings — fenced blocks by language, `####` subheads,
`---` rules, inline code, links, bold/italic.

Where it stops: it is SHAPED for the reference record schema. It reads
`verbList` / `coreList` directly. It does NOT walk generic `chapter` /
`section` / `figure` records. It has no chunking hints, no target other
than HTML, no cross-ref resolution, no image handling, no style-kit
separation (all styles baked into the emitter + `styles.css`), and no
notion of code as a queryable record.

Tonight's ~1,340 chapters (Book of Words, Book of SLAT itself, Book of
Don'ts, Book of CS Curriculum, Book of Animation, Book of Challenges, and
the rest per BOOK-INVENTORY.jsonl) live as `(chapter :prose \"...markdown
with front-matter and fenced code...\")`. They round-trip. They validate.
They just do not render — for books — yet. The 2026-07-13 authoring push
has parked ~1,340 wrapped-MD SLAT files at the door. This document is the
plan for opening it.

The gap this doc fills: extend render-ref.mjs into a general SLAT render
pipeline that (a) handles the wrapped-MD chapter shape unchanged, (b)
learns to treat code as first-class records alongside `:prose`, (c) grows
to four more targets (terminal, IDE, search, LLM-ingest), and (d)
externalizes styling into a kit written in — dogfood — SLAT.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 2 — Alfred's questions, answered
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     2
  :title "Alfred's questions, answered"
  :prose
"**Can SLAT faithfully reproduce MD?** Yes. The `:prose` field is a string;
strings round-trip byte-for-byte per Chapter 1's guarantee. Every fenced
code block, front-matter block, blockquote, `> **Sakura says**` callout,
and cross-link syntax survives read+write unchanged. The ~1,340 chapters
we've already emitted prove this in practice — their `:sha256` provenance
is intact from the original MD source, and `slat-read → slat-write` on
each returns identical bytes. So SLAT-as-MD-wrapper is not a compromise;
it's a first-class use of the format. The MD lives INSIDE a typed record
with metadata (`:book`, `:chapter-number`, `:title`, `:source-path`,
`:size`, `:sha256`) that a bare `.md` file cannot carry.

**What happens when we render SLAT to HTML?** Nothing yet, for books. For
the reference, `render-ref.mjs` does it. For books, we build a new
emitter — but not from scratch. Section 5 details a pipeline that shares
the SLAT reader + style kit across five targets. For HTML specifically,
the emitter walks the record, treats `:prose` with the same
`renderDocBody` MD subset render-ref.mjs already uses, and emits sibling
records (Section 3) into typed HTML blocks. The plan is: extend, not
rewrite.

**Chunking granularity?** Layered. A chapter declares
`:chunkable-as (:paragraph :section :chapter)` and the render pipeline
picks the level per target. Search wants paragraph chunks (snippets fit
the SERP shape). LLM ingest wants section chunks (RAG context wants
semantic units, not random 512-token windows). Rendering to HTML wants
whole-chapter chunks (one file per URL). Terminal wants section chunks
(one screenful at a time). The declaration is a HINT; the renderer honors
the smallest level that satisfies the target. Recommendation in Section
3: derive on demand from a paragraph-tokenizer applied to `:prose`,
CACHE the derivation into a sidecar `.chunks.slat` file whose
`:content-hash` binds to the parent chapter's `:sha256`. Materialization
avoids re-parsing 1,340 chapters on every build. Invalidation is trivial:
hash mismatch → recompute.

**Images and diagrams?** Three lanes, all first-class `:figure` records.
Archived / historical images ship base64-inline in `:data` so the SLAT
file is a self-contained artifact (signed, content-addressed, portable
across mailboxes and mail archives). Currently-authored images ship as
`:src \"path/or/url\"` so the SLAT stays small and the image lives in the
file tree next to the chapter (or on a CDN). Diagrams — the ones a kid
should be able to read AND edit — ship as inline SVG in `:svg`, so the
SLAT is again self-contained, human-legible (SVG is XML), and the
diagram can be regenerated by a Scheme cart the same way carts render
graphics today. Three lanes, one record type, distinguished by which
field is populated. Renderer picks the field.

**Style: inline every time or in a kit?** Kit. Every time. Content records
carry `:kind` (semantic type — `:sakura-says`, `:warning`, `:paragraph`,
`:code`, `:figure`, `:table`). The renderer carries a style kit — a
separate SLAT file — that maps each `:kind` to visual attributes per
target (HTML class + optional inline style, terminal ANSI code, IDE
hover-card badge). Alfred edits colors and spacing by editing the kit,
not by touching 1,340 chapters. Inline `:style` on a specific record is
POSSIBLE but discouraged — it exists for the one-off case where a chapter
genuinely needs to break the kit for pedagogical reasons (rare). Section
6 details the kit.

**Are SLATs fine as MD-wrappers?** Yes — as a starting point, and for
long-form narrative prose, arguably forever. The chapter narrative that a
human WROTE as prose reads best as `:prose` and the round-trip is byte-
perfect. But CODE deserves better. Code in a wrapped-MD chapter is trapped
behind an MD parse: to programmatically find every runnable example in
every book you must re-parse the fence, guess the language, and hope no
one used tildes or indented fences. Sakura and the operators deserve
first-class records for code — that's Section 4, and it's the amendment
Alfred is right to push for. Bottom line: SLAT-as-MD-wrapper is fine for
prose. Code lives BOTH in `:prose` (so MD→HTML renders) AND as sibling
records (so programmatic access needs zero MD parsing). Redundancy with
`:content-hash` verifies the two representations agree.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 3 — SLAT spec extensions (additions, not rewrite)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     3
  :title "SLAT spec extensions — additions to the record vocabulary, not a rewrite"
  :prose
"The extensions below are ADDITIONS. Nothing in Book of SLAT Chapters
1-16 changes. The `head + keys + positional + comment` shape stands.
The `:_` reserved namespace stands. The canonical writer, the round-trip
guarantee, the content-addressing rules — all stand. What follows is a
catalog of NEW record heads with well-defined semantics that the
render pipeline knows how to walk.

**Content record types.** These describe pieces of a book.

  (chapter    :book \"...\" :chapter-number N :title \"...\"
              :prose \"...\"                    ; MD-wrapped, current shape
              :chunkable-as (:paragraph :section :chapter)
              :children [(section ...) (section ...) ...])

  (appendix   :book \"...\" :letter \"A\" :title \"...\" :prose \"...\")

  (index      :book \"...\" :entries [(entry :term \"...\" :ref \"...\") ...])

  (section    :heading \"...\" :level N :prose \"...\"
              :children [...])

  (paragraph  :text \"...\"
              :kind :paragraph)               ; default

  (sakura-says :text \"...\")                  ; the callout box shape

  (warning    :text \"...\" :severity :info|:warn|:hazard)

  (quote      :text \"...\" :attribution \"...\" :source \"...\")

  (aside      :text \"...\")                   ; sidebar / margin note

  (figure     :caption \"...\"
              :src \"path/or/url\"              ; ONE of these three
              :data \"base64-bytes...\"        ;   is populated per figure
              :svg \"<svg>...</svg>\"          ;   per Section 2
              :alt \"...\"
              :width N :height N)

  (table      :caption \"...\"
              :headers [\"col1\" \"col2\" ...]
              :rows [[...] [...] ...])

  (cross-ref  :to-book \"...\"
              :to-chapter N
              :to-record-id \"...\"            ; anchors within a chapter
              :label \"...\")                  ; display text

**Chunk hints — pre-materialized or derived on demand?** Recommendation:
derived on demand, sidecar-cached. When a chapter carries
`:chunkable-as (:paragraph :section :chapter)`, the pipeline runs a
paragraph tokenizer on `:prose` at BUILD time, emits a companion file
`<chapter-file>.chunks.slat` containing a `(chunks :parent-hash \"...\"
:paragraphs [...] :sections [...])` record, and binds it to the parent
chapter's `:sha256`. On subsequent builds, if `parent-hash` matches, the
cache is reused. If not, recompute. This means:

  - Author edits `:prose` → sha changes → chunk cache invalidates → rebuild
  - No manual maintenance of chunk boundaries in the source SLAT
  - Chunks are addressable independently for search + LLM ingest
  - Author does not have to think about chunking at all

The alternative — pre-materializing chunks as sibling records at author
time — clutters the source and creates a maintenance hazard (author edits
`:prose`, forgets to re-chunk, chunks drift). Rejected.

**Style semantics — content carries kind, renderer carries kit.** Every
content record accepts a `:kind` field. Defaults are derived from the
record head (`(sakura-says ...)` implies `:kind :sakura-says`,
`(paragraph ...)` implies `:kind :paragraph`). The renderer resolves
`:kind` against the currently-loaded style kit (Section 6) to determine
visual output. A record MAY carry `:style` for inline override — it's
supported for pedagogical exceptions but discouraged; overuse fragments
the visual system. The kit is where colors, spacing, typographic
choices live. The kit IS a SLAT file (dogfood). Section 6 details.

**Cross-refs.** A `(cross-ref ...)` resolves at RENDER time. The
resolver walks the book+chapter+record-id triple:

  - `:to-book \"Book of SLAT\"` → look up the book by name
  - `:to-chapter 4`             → look up the chapter within the book
  - `:to-record-id \"the-shape\"` → look up an anchor within the chapter

For HTML, the resolver emits `<a href=\"/books/book-of-slat/ch04#the-shape\">
label</a>` plus optional hover-preview data attributes. For terminal, it
emits a labeled section reference the user can jump to via a REPL verb.
For LLM ingest, it emits a resolved chunk reference so RAG can hop the
graph. For search, it's a backlink signal (chapters with many incoming
cross-refs rank higher).

Anchors within a chapter are recommended — record authors can carry
`:id \"the-shape\"` on any record that a cross-ref might target. The
render pipeline slugifies missing ids from headings the same way
render-ref.mjs already does (`slugify()` + counter suffix).

**Preserving existing provenance.** The current wrapped-MD chapters
carry `:sha256` and `:source-path`. Both stay. The chunk cache binds to
`:sha256`. The build system uses `:source-path` for reverse lookup
(operator says 'edit chapter 4 of Book of SLAT' → resolver finds the
file). The extensions ADD to this metadata; nothing removes it.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 4 — Code as first-class SLAT records (Alfred's amendment)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     4
  :title "Code as first-class SLAT records — the redundancy pattern that unlocks query"
  :prose
"Alfred's amendment: code deserves first-class records. This section
specifies what that looks like without breaking anything the wrapped-MD
chapters already do.

**The record types.**

  (example
    :kind        :example
    :lang        :scheme
    :body        \"(define (square x) (* x x))\\n(square 5)\"
    :runnable    #t
    :expected    \"25\"
    :parent      \"book-of-slat/ch01#the-second-slat\"
    :order       2)                    ; nth code block in the chapter

  (code
    :kind        :code
    :lang        :scheme
    :body        \"; illustrative only — do not run\\n(define x ...)\"
    :runnable    #f
    :parent      \"...\"
    :order       N)

  (cart-embed
    :kind        :cart-embed
    :cart-id     'shop/new-listing-v3
    :body        \"(cart :head 'shop/new-listing-v3 ...)\"
    :installable #t
    :tier        :green
    :parent      \"...\"
    :order       N)

  (repl-transcript
    :kind        :repl-transcript
    :turns       [(:input \"(+ 1 2)\" :output \"3\")
                  (:input \"(* 4 5)\" :output \"20\")]
    :parent      \"...\"
    :order       N)

  (output
    :kind             :output
    :from-example-order  2
    :text             \"25\"
    :parent           \"...\")

The `:parent` field points back to a chapter+anchor. `:order` disambiguates
multiple code blocks within one chapter. `:runnable #t` means the pipeline
should render a Run button and the LLM ingest pipeline should include this
as a verified SFT training pair (input=body, output=expected).

**The redundancy pattern.** Code lives BOTH in the parent chapter's
`:prose` (as a Markdown fenced block, so MD→HTML rendering works with zero
special-casing) AND as a sibling `(example ...)` / `(code ...)` /
`(cart-embed ...)` record (so programmatic access needs no MD parsing).
The two representations must agree; a `:content-hash` field on the sibling
record binds to the exact bytes inside the MD fence:

  (example
    ...
    :body \"(define (square x) (* x x))\\n(square 5)\"
    :content-hash \"sha256:abc123...\")

At build time, the extractor (Phase 2 in Section 7) verifies for every
sibling record that hashing the corresponding fence content produces
`:content-hash`. Mismatch = build fails, author edits `:prose`, extractor
re-emits siblings. The invariant is checked, not trusted.

**The query API this enables.** Sakura and operator tooling gain:

  ;; every runnable Scheme example across every book
  (select :kind :example :lang :scheme :runnable #t)

  ;; every cart embedded in Book of Music
  (select :kind :cart-embed :book \"Book of Music\")

  ;; the code at chapter 3, block 2, of Book of SLAT
  (select :book \"Book of SLAT\" :chapter-number 3 :order 2)

  ;; every REPL transcript that mentions error handling
  (select :kind :repl-transcript :turns-contain \"error\")

No MD parsing anywhere. The query walks record indexes. Result: milliseconds
across the entire book corpus.

**Killer use cases.**

  - **Interactive REPL cells in the browser.** Every `(example ... :runnable
    #t)` renders as a Run button (already done in render-ref.mjs);
    additionally, the pipeline can lift the block into an editable REPL
    cell where the reader edits and re-runs. Same code that runs in the
    reference now runs in the books.

  - **IDE hover 'Run this'.** LSP hover on a code fence in the source SLAT
    surfaces the `(example ...)` record, its expected output, its parent
    chapter, and a Run action. The IDE calls back into the runtime, runs,
    diffs against `:expected`.

  - **Sakura pulls carts on-demand.** A `(cart-embed ...)` record is a
    first-class installable. Sakura sees `:cart-id`, looks up the operator
    tier gating, and offers install with a one-line explanation from the
    parent chapter's context.

  - **Training data.** LLM ingest walks `(example ... :runnable #t
    :expected ...)` records and emits SFT pairs directly. No fence parsing,
    no ambiguous 'is this Scheme or output?' problem. Every pair carries
    provenance back to a chapter, book, author.

  - **Regression testing.** Nightly build runs every `(example ...
    :runnable #t)` in the corpus and diffs actual output against
    `:expected`. Book that doesn't work anymore = red build. Trust in
    the pedagogy is a CI signal.

  - **Migration safety net.** When a verb signature changes and 43
    examples across 12 books use it, the query API finds them all in
    milliseconds. The old world required a grep+regex sweep across MD.

**Extraction plan for the ~1,340 existing wrapped-MD files.** One pass,
one script:

  1. Read each `(chapter ... :prose \"...\")` record
  2. Scan `:prose` for fenced code blocks — reuse the same regex the
     current `renderDocBody` uses (`^\\`\\`\\` <lang>`)
  3. For each fence, compute `:content-hash` over the fence body
  4. Emit a sibling record based on lang and heuristics:
     - `sakura-scheme` / `scheme` / `scm` → `(example :runnable #t)`
       (heuristic: if the block ends with an expression that produces a
       value, it's runnable; if it starts with `;;` and defines only,
       still runnable)
     - `text` / `output` / no-lang and immediately follows a scheme block
       → `(output :from-example-order N)`
     - anything with `(cart ...)` head symbol → `(cart-embed ...)`
     - other lang → `(code :lang <lang> :runnable #f)`
  5. Set `:parent`, `:order`, `:content-hash`
  6. Write the sibling records into the same file OR a companion
     `.code.slat` (Section 7 defers this choice to Phase 2)

`:prose` stays untouched. The MD renderer keeps working. The new pipeline
gains query. The two coexist. That is the whole point of the redundancy
pattern.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 5 — Render pipeline architecture (five targets)
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     5
  :title "Render pipeline architecture — five targets, one reader, one kit"
  :prose
"The pipeline is shaped like a T. The vertical stroke is shared: SLAT
reader (`slat-loader.js` / `reference-loader.js`) parses records, the
style kit (Section 6) provides visual attributes, the chunk cache (Section
3) provides pre-materialized boundaries. The horizontal stroke is
target-specific emitters. Five today.

**Terminal.** For the kid running `sakura-scheme repl` who types
`(book 'book-of-slat :chapter 1)` and expects a page to appear. Emitter
uses box-drawing characters for figures, ANSI 256-color codes mapped from
the kit's terminal palette, monospace column layout with soft-wrap at 80
columns default (respects `$COLUMNS`). Code blocks render with syntax
highlighting via ANSI color; the reference verb `run-example` on the head
line lets the reader execute in-place. `(figure :svg ...)` renders as
ASCII-art via a small svg-to-ascii routine for the simple cases and a
`[figure: <caption>]` placeholder otherwise. `(cross-ref ...)` renders as
`[→ Book of X, ch N]` and becomes a jumpable target via a REPL verb. This
is the surface for the North Georgia kid — no browser needed, works over
SSH, works offline.

**IDE.** For the developer editing a `.slat` file in VS Code (or any LSP
client). Emitter is the LSP server — it does not produce a static file;
it responds to hover/complete/references requests. Hover on a code fence
inside `:prose` surfaces the corresponding `(example ...)` sibling record
as a hover card: expected output, parent chapter, tier if it's a
cart-embed. Gutter icons: Run for `:runnable #t`, Install for
`:installable #t`, Jump-to-def for `:cross-ref`. Cross-refs resolve to
file positions across the workspace. This surface makes SLAT authoring
feel like editing code with tests — because that's what it is.

**Web (HTML).** For the operator on `sakura.lacunalabs.ai`. Emitter is a
generalized `render-book.mjs` that reuses render-ref.mjs's Scheme
highlighter, `renderDocBody`, `renderCodeBlock`, and `renderInline`. New
work: walk arbitrary `(chapter ...)` / `(section ...)` records, resolve
`(cross-ref ...)` to `<a href>` + hover-preview data attributes, render
`(figure ...)` with the three-lane logic from Section 2, render
`(sakura-says ...)` / `(warning ...)` / `(quote ...)` as styled callouts
per the kit. REPL cells become interactive: click Run and the browser
posts the body to the same REPL endpoint the reference already uses. Sidebar
TOC uses the same anchor pattern render-ref.mjs uses.

**Search.** For the operator typing 'how do I sign a cart?' into the
search box. Emitter builds an index from chunk records: paragraph chunks
provide snippet text, section chunks provide semantic groupings, chapter
records provide titles + URLs. Ranking uses cross-ref graph as a backlink
signal, `:kind :sakura-says` chunks boost slightly (Sakura's callouts are
lesson-shaped), and code chunks appear as separate results 'code example'
with a snippet of the body. The index is a set of SLAT records too —
`(search-index :entries [...])` — dogfooded, content-addressed, rebuildable
from the corpus at any time.

**LLM ingest.** For the training pipeline. Emitter walks the corpus at
the section-chunk level (the semantic unit is what a language model needs
for RAG and SFT), emits JSONL where each row carries: chunk text,
provenance (book+chapter+anchor), `:kind`, cross-ref out-edges (for
training the model to follow the cross-ref graph), and — critically — the
verified code sibling records as separate rows tagged `:sft-pair`. The
training pipeline treats `(example ... :runnable #t :expected ...)` as
gold pairs. Nothing is invented from the MD; every training row cites a
record. This is the corpus infrastructure that makes SFT trustworthy.

**What is shared.** SLAT reader. Chunk cache. Cross-ref resolver. Style
kit. Scheme highlighter (rendering to ANSI vs HTML spans is a small
per-target adapter). Content-hash verifier.

**What is target-specific.** The emitter. Terminal emits ANSI strings.
IDE emits LSP responses. Web emits HTML strings. Search emits index rows.
LLM ingest emits JSONL rows. Each is a small module that consumes the
same in-memory record graph.

This shape means adding a sixth target — say, print/PDF — is a new
emitter, not a new pipeline.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 6 — Style kit design
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     6
  :title "Style kit design — the visual contract, in SLAT"
  :prose
"Style kits live at `~/code/curator/scheme-books/.style-kits/<name>.slat`.
A kit is a SLAT record that maps `:kind` values to visual attributes per
target. Multiple named kits ship; the renderer takes a `--kit` flag or a
book-level `:default-kit` declaration.

**Example kit — the default.**

  ;; ~/code/curator/scheme-books/.style-kits/default.slat
  (style-kit
    :name    \"default\"
    :version 1
    :for-books (\"Book of SLAT\" \"Book of Words\" \"Book of Reason\" *)
    :kinds
    ((:paragraph
        :html    (:tag \"p\" :class \"prose-p\")
        :terminal (:indent 0 :wrap 80)
        :ide     (:hover nil))

     (:sakura-says
        :html    (:tag \"blockquote\" :class \"sakura-callout\"
                  :prefix \"<strong>Sakura says</strong>\")
        :terminal (:box :single :prefix \"Sakura says\"
                   :color :magenta)
        :ide     (:hover (:badge \"Sakura\" :color \"#e91e63\")))

     (:warning
        :html    (:tag \"aside\" :class \"warning-{severity}\")
        :terminal (:box :double :color :yellow)
        :ide     (:hover (:badge \"Warning\" :color \"#f57c00\")))

     (:code
        :html    (:tag \"pre\" :class \"code {lang}\"
                  :children ((:tag \"code\" :highlight scheme)))
        :terminal (:box :single :highlight scheme)
        :ide     (:hover (:show-expected #t)))

     (:figure
        :html    (:tag \"figure\" :class \"figure\"
                  :caption-tag \"figcaption\")
        :terminal (:svg-to-ascii #t :fallback \"[figure: {caption}]\")
        :ide     (:hover nil))

     (:cross-ref
        :html    (:tag \"a\" :class \"cross-ref\"
                  :href \"{book-slug}/ch{chapter}#{record-id}\"
                  :hover-preview #t)
        :terminal (:format \"[→ {label}]\")
        :ide     (:definition {book}/{chapter}/{record-id}))))

**Named kits ship out of the box.**

  - `default` — the current visual identity of sakura.lacunalabs.ai
  - `kid-friendly` — larger type, more color, softer contrast
  - `terminal` — the terminal-target defaults, extracted so a CI job can
    render every book to text for archival
  - `print` — grayscale, higher-density type, no interactive elements
  - `high-contrast` — a11y variant, WCAG AAA

**Contract.** A kit MUST provide entries for all `:kind` values the render
pipeline recognizes. If a book uses a `:kind` the kit doesn't map, the
renderer falls back to a bare tag with the `:kind` name as the class name
(HTML) or a `[{:kind}: ...]` labeled block (terminal). This means a new
`:kind` can ship in a chapter before the kit is updated — the fallback
degrades gracefully.

**Why in SLAT?** Dogfood. Alfred edits colors by editing a SLAT record.
The kit is content-addressed, signable, versionable — same substrate as
everything else. It composes with SLAT's canonical writer (kit changes
have a hash; a book renders differently when the kit hash changes; the
build system can detect this).

**Author overrides.** A specific chapter can override the kit locally:

  (chapter
    :book \"Book of SLAT\"
    :chapter-number 4
    ...
    :override-style ((:code (:html (:tag \"pre\" :class \"code emphasized\"))))
    :prose \"...\")

This is DISCOURAGED but supported. The renderer merges override on top of
the loaded kit, per-kind. Use it when a chapter genuinely needs to break
the visual system — rare; if a book needs to break it often, that's a
signal that the kit itself should change.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 7 — Concrete implementation plan
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     7
  :title "Concrete implementation plan — phased, with hour estimates where honest"
  :prose
"Phase 0 estimates are grounded in the shape of `render-ref.mjs` (334 lines
of JS with a working highlighter + inline MD subset — a solid extension
point). Later phases carry TBD because the scope expands multiplicatively
with each target added.

**Phase 0 — Extend render-ref.mjs to handle generic SLAT chapter records
with MD-in-`:prose`.**  8-12 hours.

Deliverables:
  - `docs/site/render-book.mjs` — new file, shares helpers with
    render-ref.mjs (`highlightScheme`, `renderDocBody`, `renderInline`,
    `renderCodeBlock`, `slugify`, `esc`)
  - Extract shared helpers into `docs/site/render-shared.mjs`
  - New emitter walks `(chapter ...)`, `(section ...)`, `(sakura-says
    ...)`, `(warning ...)`, `(quote ...)`, `(figure ...)` records
  - Reads `:prose` MD via existing `renderDocBody`
  - Emits `dist/books/<slug>/ch<N>.html` per chapter
  - Sidebar TOC per book
  - No style kit yet — inline styles matching current sakura.lacunalabs.ai
    identity
  - No cross-ref resolution yet — cross-refs render as plain text link
    placeholders

Verification:
  - Rendering Book of SLAT chapters 0-4 produces HTML that visually matches
    the current MD render (which today has to be done by hand)
  - Byte-for-byte round-trip of `:prose` — the MD in the output HTML source
    matches the MD in the SLAT input

**Phase 1 — Chunk hints + LLM ingest pipeline.**  6-10 hours.

Deliverables:
  - Paragraph tokenizer (splits `:prose` on double-newline, respects
    fenced blocks as atomic)
  - Section tokenizer (splits on `##` / `###` headings within `:prose`)
  - Sidecar `.chunks.slat` writer, keyed by parent `:sha256`
  - Cache invalidation on hash mismatch
  - `render-llm-ingest.mjs` emitter → JSONL rows tagged
    `{book, chapter, anchor, kind, text, cross-refs, sft-pair?}`

Verification:
  - Re-running the build on unchanged corpus produces byte-identical
    `.chunks.slat` files (deterministic per SLAT canonicalization)
  - Every JSONL row cites a resolvable record

**Phase 2 — Code extraction pass over the ~1,340 chapters.**  4-6 hours.

Deliverables:
  - `scripts/extract-code-records.mjs` — one-shot
  - Walks every SLAT chapter, scans `:prose` for fenced blocks
  - Emits `(example ...)` / `(code ...)` / `(cart-embed ...)` / `(output
    ...)` / `(repl-transcript ...)` sibling records
  - Content-hash verification
  - Emits into a companion `<chapter>.code.slat` file (keeps `:prose`
    pristine; keeps `git diff` on prose separable from code metadata)
  - Dry-run mode reports counts by kind and detects ambiguous fences for
    author review

Verification:
  - Every `(example ... :runnable #t)` extracted from a Scheme fence
    parses under `slat-read`
  - Nightly `run-all-examples` CI job diffs actuals against `:expected` on
    a sample of ~100 records (grows over time)

**Phase 3 — Media records + cross-refs.**  8-12 hours.

Deliverables:
  - `(figure ...)` renderer with three-lane logic (`:src`, `:data`,
    `:svg`)
  - `(table ...)` renderer (HTML `<table>`, terminal box-draw)
  - `(cross-ref ...)` resolver: builds a global anchor index across all
    books at build time, resolves `:to-book` + `:to-chapter` +
    `:to-record-id` into a URL + hover-preview payload
  - HTML hover-preview: on `:hover`, fetch the target chunk's first
    paragraph as tooltip
  - Anchor-id backfill: chapters without `:id` on records get slugified
    ids from headings

Verification:
  - Every cross-ref in the corpus resolves OR is reported as a build
    error
  - Circular/broken cross-refs surface with source path + line

**Phase 4 — Terminal + IDE targets.**  TBD after Phase 0.

The scope depends on how much of Phase 0's shared helpers can be
retargeted vs. rebuilt. Estimate after Phase 0 completes and the shared/
target boundary is empirical.

Terminal deliverables (sketch):
  - `render-terminal.mjs` — walks records, emits ANSI-decorated strings
  - `sakura-scheme repl` verb: `(book :name ... :chapter N)` prints the
    chapter
  - Box-draw for `(figure ...)`, `(sakura-says ...)`, `(warning ...)`

IDE deliverables (sketch):
  - `sakura-scheme-lsp` server exposing hover, definition, references
  - VS Code extension consumes the LSP
  - Gutter Run icons trigger REPL execution via the language runtime

**Phase 5 — Search index.**  TBD after Phase 1 (depends on chunk shape
being stable).

**Style kit — cross-cutting.** The style-kit spec (Section 6)
is authored during Phase 0 and consumed starting Phase 3 (when the visual
system stops being ad-hoc inline styles and starts being kit-driven). Kit
work is ~3-5 hours interleaved.

**Total to a rendered book corpus with code query + LLM ingest + cross-
refs:** roughly 26-40 hours across Phases 0-3, before Phase 4/5 targets.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 8 — What we extend, not rewrite
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     8
  :title "What we extend, not rewrite — the surfaces that already work"
  :prose
"Three modules stay. Any rewrite temptation is a rewrite of scope, not a
rewrite of code.

**`~/code/scheme-lang/docs/site/render-ref.mjs`** — extend by extracting
its helpers into `render-shared.mjs` (used by the new `render-book.mjs`)
and keeping the existing reference-emit code path intact. The reference
site keeps building the same way; the book site is a new emitter that
consumes the same helpers. Zero regression on the reference.

**`~/code/scheme-lang/src/slat-loader.js`** — the SLAT reader. It works,
it is the single source of truth for the round-trip guarantee, and every
new emitter reads through it. Do not fork it, do not shim it, do not add
a book-only variant. If the loader needs a new capability (say, tolerant
mode for a specific book), extend it in-place with a flag.

**`~/code/scheme-lang/src/reference-loader.js`** — the wrapper that
produces `ref.verbList` / `ref.coreList` from the reference SLAT. Keep
it. Add a peer `book-loader.js` that produces `book.chapters` /
`book.appendices` / `book.anchors` from a book SLAT (or set of files).
The two loaders share the underlying reader and each shape their output
for their consumer.

**Do not touch.** The canonical writer. The content-addressing rules.
The MD in `:prose` (Phase 2 emits SIBLINGS, not replacements). The
Scheme highlighter (extend if a new lang is needed; do not refactor the
tokenizer during a render sprint). `styles.css` for the reference site
(new `styles-book.css` for the book site, or a shared file split by
section).

**Rule of thumb.** If the change fits behind a new file or a new arg on
an existing function, extend. If it wants to rewrite an interface a
downstream consumer depends on, stop and ask.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Section 9 — Risks + open questions for Alfred
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(section
  :n     9
  :title "Risks + open questions for Alfred (decisions before Phase 0 fires)"
  :prose
"None of these are blockers for the general shape — but each one, if left
unanswered, becomes a small tax multiplied across ~1,340 chapters.

**Q1. Companion file vs same file for extracted code records.** Phase 2
proposes `<chapter>.code.slat` as a companion. Rationale: `git diff` on
prose stays separable from code metadata, and re-runs of the extractor
are idempotent without touching the author's source. Alternative:
extracted records go into the same file as sibling top-level records
inside the chapter. Cleaner in one sense (one file per chapter), messier
in another (extractor writes into author's file). RECOMMENDATION:
companion file. **Alfred decides.**

**Q2. Chunk cache location.** Same question, different artifact.
`<chapter>.chunks.slat` companion file, or an out-of-tree cache in
`~/.cache/curator/chunks/`? Companion file makes chunks reviewable in
git and reproducible without a cache warm. Out-of-tree keeps the source
tree clean. RECOMMENDATION: companion file for now; move to out-of-tree
if chunk artifacts become a git noise problem. **Alfred confirms.**

**Q3. Cross-ref break policy.** When a `(cross-ref ...)` cannot be
resolved, does the build fail, warn, or emit a placeholder? Reference
material treats broken refs as build errors. Book material may want
gentler treatment during authoring. RECOMMENDATION: warn during author
mode, fail on release build. **Alfred sets the release gate.**

**Q4. Kit ownership.** Where does the `default` kit live for editing?
`~/code/curator/scheme-books/.style-kits/` is proposed but it means the
kit ships with the corpus, not with the renderer. Alternative: kit lives
in `~/code/scheme-lang/docs/site/kits/` alongside the renderer.
RECOMMENDATION: with the corpus — Alfred edits book visuals when he
edits book content. But if he wants renderer + kit versioned together,
it moves. **Alfred picks.**

**Q5. Run-button endpoint for the book site.** The reference site already
has a REPL endpoint. The book site can reuse it or run in-page via
WASM/JS. RECOMMENDATION: reuse the reference site's REPL endpoint in
Phase 0, evaluate in-page execution in Phase 3+. **No decision needed
for Phase 0.**

**Q6. Base64 image size cap.** `(figure :data \"...\")` inlines base64.
For a 500KB PNG that's ~680KB of SLAT. Cap at some limit and require
`:src` above it? RECOMMENDATION: 100KB cap on `:data`, above which the
extractor / linter warns and suggests `:src`. **Alfred confirms cap.**

**Q7. Sibling-record collision with existing `:prose` slugs.**
render-ref.mjs uses `slugify(text) + '-' + counter` for heading anchors.
If a chapter regenerates its slugs on every build, cross-refs pointing
to counter-suffixed anchors break. Solution: prefer author-supplied
`:id` on records, fall back to stable-slug (hash of the heading text,
not counter). RECOMMENDATION: stable-slug hash for auto-generated
anchors. **Alfred confirms.**

**Risks (not questions).**

  - **Corpus scale.** ~1,340 chapters, some large. Naive per-record
    parsing on every build costs. Chunk cache + content-hash
    invalidation is not optional — Phase 1 must ship WITH Phase 0 for
    build times to stay honest.
  - **Kit drift.** Multiple named kits invite the visual system to
    fragment. Mitigation: CI check that every `:kind` in the corpus
    resolves in every named kit, or falls back cleanly.
  - **Cross-ref graph rot.** Books evolve. Anchors move. Broken cross-
    refs accumulate silently unless the build fails on them. Mitigation:
    strict cross-ref check on release builds (Q3).
  - **Code-extraction drift.** `:prose` fence changes without extractor
    re-run mean sibling records go stale. Mitigation: `:content-hash`
    verification is a CI gate (Section 4).
  - **The `:_` reserved namespace.** Section 4 introduces new kinds
    (`:parent`, `:order`, `:content-hash`). None start with `:_` so
    they are legal per Chapter 4. But `:content-hash` overlaps
    semantically with SLAT's built-in content-addressing (Chapter 9). We
    should either use SLAT's canonical hash directly or namespace the
    field as `:code-content-hash` to avoid confusion. RECOMMENDATION:
    use SLAT's canonical content-hash function; name the field
    `:body-hash` to make it clear it hashes only `:body`. **Naming
    decision Alfred can confirm.**

That is the full plan. Phase 0 can start once Q1, Q2, Q4, Q7 are
answered (Q3 and Q6 come up later). None of the answers are load-bearing
for the shape.")


;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; End of strategy doc
;; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(end-of-doc
  :sections-landed 9
  :next-action     "Alfred reviews Section 9 questions; Phase 0 fires once Q1/Q2/Q4/Q7 answered."
  :owner           "Lacuna Engineering")
